  <content>
    <title>Strategy Methods: Solution Options and Limitation Assessment</title>

    <summary>Toolkit for weighted multi-criteria scoring of solution options, limitation/defect assessment, and BABOK 50-technique lookup. Without a structured scoring method, solution recommendations are driven by advocacy rather than evidence. Weighted criteria scoring forces explicit trade-offs; sensitivity analysis reveals whether the recommendation is robust or brittle. Limitation registers with 5-whys root causes prevent remediation from landing on symptoms.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Solution decisions without structured analysis are driven by pre-existing vendor preferences, organizational politics, or the loudest voice in the room. Weighted multi-criteria scoring forces explicit trade-offs and documents the rationale behind each decision.</p>
      <p>Sensitivity analysis (±10% and ±25% weight perturbation) reveals whether the recommendation is statistically robust or a coin-flip. A recommendation that flips winner under small weight changes should not be published without flagging the brittleness to decision-makers.</p>
      <p>Limitation assessment without root-cause analysis produces band-aid remediations that fail again next quarter. The 5-whys method with evidence anchor prevents restating symptoms as causes.</p>
      <p>BABOK defines 50 BA techniques; naive agents pick the famous ones (SWOT, PESTLE) without checking applicability. A technique router indexed by use case enables agents to select the right tool for the specific context.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Two or more solution options exist (build/buy/partner/SaaS/status-quo) and a sponsor needs a defensible recommendation with a numeric weighted score</item>
        <item>Vendor/RFP shortlists where 3-5 finalists must be reduced to a single recommendation</item>
        <item>Architecture decisions where competing patterns need comparison beyond gut feel</item>
        <item>Post-deployment when users surface defects and someone must decide fix/workaround/accept/defer</item>
        <item>Steering-committee decision packs requiring alternatives, criteria, weights, and sensitivity analysis</item>
        <item>Quick BA technique lookup: matching a sub-task to the right BABOK technique from the 50-technique reference</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>One option with an obvious winner — do not invent strawman alternatives to fill a matrix</item>
        <item>Reversible/two-way-door decisions (feature flag, copy change, small refactor) — use a one-line ADR</item>
        <item>Decisions dominated by a single hard constraint (regulatory deadline, cost ceiling) — filter on that constraint alone</item>
        <item>Pure quantitative cash-flow comparisons — use NPV/IRR/payback instead</item>
        <item>Limitation assessment for incidents with a known cause and an in-flight patch — use post-mortem/5-whys</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="options-identification-and-scoring">
      <p>Weighted multi-criteria scoring rules: options identification, criteria weighting, anchored scoring rubric, sensitivity analysis, and recommendation constraints.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always include status-quo (do-nothing) as a numbered option in the scoring matrix and weighted totals; never omit it.</statement>
        <rationale>Without status-quo as Option A, leadership cannot see the cost of inaction; the recommendation reads as advocacy rather than analysis.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Generate 3-7 alternatives before scoring; do not begin scoring with a single option and a strawman.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-option matrices are decorative; sponsors recognize them as advocacy and the technique gets discredited for the next real decision.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Lock criteria weights before options are scored, in a separate step with named stakeholders; never let the scoring agent set weights.</statement>
        <rationale>Weights drift to make the math agree with the pre-decided recommendation. The weight-setting step must be documented separately so the rationale survives later challenge.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Treat any weight sum that does not equal 100% as an error; do not silently normalize.</statement>
        <rationale>Silent normalization hides input errors and changes the effective weight of every criterion without the stakeholder knowing.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Cap the criterion list at 5-7; more criteria collapse to ties and double-counting.</statement>
        <rationale>Above 7 criteria, marginal criteria carry less than 3% weight — they add noise, not signal, and often encode the same underlying dimension twice.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Criteria that partially overlap (e.g., Cost, Time to value, and Risk all encoding capital exposure).</description>
        <reason>Double-counting inflates one dimension and makes the matrix systematically biased toward options that score well on capital risk, even when that was not the intent.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="anchored-scoring">
      <p>Anchor every score on the 1-5 rubric to a measurable definition before scoring begins; free-form 1-5 produces clustering at 3-4.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Anchor every score on the 1-5 rubric to a measurable definition before scoring begins; free-form 1-5 produces clustering at 3-4.</statement>
        <rationale>Without anchors, every option scores 3 or 4 on every criterion; differences wash out and the matrix produces no ranking signal.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <note>Anchored rubric for "Strategic fit": 5 = exceeds strategic target by ≥20%, 4 = meets target, 3 = neutral/unclear, 2 = partial misalignment, 1 = direct conflict with strategy.</note>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>Require at least one evidence_url per (option, criterion) cell; mark any cell without evidence confidence=low and force score to 3.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs cluster scores at 3-4 and will hallucinate vendor pricing or TCO numbers that "feel right." Evidence anchors prevent fabrication.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="sensitivity-analysis">
      <p>Run ±10% and ±25% weight perturbation and single-criterion-removal on every published matrix; if the winner flips under ≤10% perturbation, set brittleness=high and require human review before publishing.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run ±10% and ±25% weight perturbation and single-criterion-removal on every published matrix; if the winner flips under ≤10% perturbation, set brittleness=high and require human review before publishing.</statement>
        <rationale>A recommendation that flips on a 10% weight wobble is statistically a coin-flip; publishing it without the brittleness flag misleads sponsors.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# sensitivity.py: weight perturbation analysis
# Input: scoring matrix + baseline weights
# Output: ranking at ±10%, ±25%, brittleness flag

def sensitivity_analysis(matrix, weights, options):
    """
    Perturbation: for each criterion weight, vary by ±10% and ±25%.
    Recompute weighted score and re-rank.
    Flag brittleness if winner changes.
    """
    base_ranking = rank_options(matrix, weights, options)
    winner_base = base_ranking[0]['option_id']
    flips = []

    for i, criterion in enumerate(weights):
        for perturbation in [0.90, 0.75, 1.10, 1.25]:
            w_perturbed = weights.copy()
            w_perturbed[i] *= perturbation
            # Re-normalize to 100%
            w_perturbed = [w / sum(w_perturbed) * 100 for w in w_perturbed]

            perturbed_ranking = rank_options(matrix, w_perturbed, options)
            winner_perturbed = perturbed_ranking[0]['option_id']

            if winner_perturbed != winner_base:
                flips.append({
                    'criterion': criterion,
                    'perturbation': perturbation,
                    'winner_flips_to': winner_perturbed
                })

    brittleness = 'high' if any(f['perturbation'] in [0.90, 1.10] for f in flips) else 'low'
    return {
        'base_winner': winner_base,
        'flips': flips,
        'brittleness': brittleness
    }
]]></code>
        <note>Python utility for weight perturbation and brittleness detection.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="limitation-identification-and-assessment">
      <p>Limitation assessment covers identification from multiple sources, root-cause requirements via 5-whys, severity derivation formula, and remediation options analysis.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Extract limitations from defect logs, support tickets, and at least one user-research source; never from team memory alone.</statement>
        <rationale>Tickets-only over-weights the loudest 5 customers; user-research corroboration identifies silent majority pain points that tickets never surface.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Require a minimum 3-entry 5-whys chain for every limitation row; reject any row where the root_cause restates the symptom description.</statement>
        <rationale>Remediation that lands on symptoms produces the same defect next quarter; only root-cause-anchored remediation is durable.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="bad">
        <note>Limitation: "Export fails for large datasets." Root cause: "Export fails for large datasets." — This is symptom restatement, not root cause. Reject this row and re-run with 5-whys drill.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good">
        <note>5-whys chain: (1) Export fails → (2) timeout at 30s → (3) synchronous processing → (4) no async job queue → (5) batch design was never planned for >10k rows. Root cause category: technical. Remediation: implement async export job.</note>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>Derive severity from a numeric formula (users_affected × frequency × business_impact); never assert severity without showing the math.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a numeric formula, every limitation is tagged "High" within a week of the register opening — prioritization breaks entirely.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list title="Severity Levels">
        <item>Critical: affects &gt;50% of users, occurs daily, blocks core business process.</item>
        <item>High: affects &gt;20% of users, occurs weekly, creates significant workaround burden.</item>
        <item>Medium: affects &lt;20% of users, occurs monthly, has viable workaround.</item>
        <item>Low: affects &lt;5% of users, rare, cosmetic or minor inconvenience.</item>
      </list>

      <rule>
        <statement>Document "Accept" remediation only when every cheaper option (fix, workaround, defer) is explicitly listed and rejected with rationale.</statement>
        <rationale>Accepting without exhausting alternatives is not a decision — it is inaction dressed up as analysis.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="babok-50-technique-lookup">
      <p>BABOK defines 50 BA techniques. Use this section as a router to select the right technique for a given context. After selecting by name, read the BABOK inputs/outputs/applicability section before applying.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use the BABOK-50 table as a router only; after selecting a technique by name, read the BABOK inputs/outputs/applicability section before applying it.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents picking techniques by name match without checking BABOK applicability produce the wrong artifact for the context — "Decision Analysis" selected for a prioritization task when "Prioritization" was the correct technique.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list title="BABOK 50-Technique Index">
        <item>1 — Acceptance and Evaluation Criteria: requirements validation, acceptance testing.</item>
        <item>2 — Backlog Management: agile requirements, iteration planning.</item>
        <item>3 — Balanced Scorecard: strategy analysis, performance measurement.</item>
        <item>4 — Benchmarking and Market Analysis: current state analysis, competitive positioning.</item>
        <item>5 — Brainstorming: elicitation, idea generation.</item>
        <item>6 — Business Capability Analysis: strategy analysis, gap identification.</item>
        <item>7 — Business Cases: change strategy, investment justification.</item>
        <item>8 — Business Model Canvas: strategy analysis, business model design.</item>
        <item>9 — Business Rules Analysis: requirements analysis, rule documentation.</item>
        <item>10 — Collaborative Games: elicitation, team alignment.</item>
        <item>11 — Concept Modelling: requirements modeling, domain vocabulary.</item>
        <item>12 — Data Dictionary: data requirements, system integration.</item>
        <item>13 — Data Flow Diagrams: process analysis, system boundary definition.</item>
        <item>14 — Data Mining: analysis, pattern discovery.</item>
        <item>15 — Data Modelling: data requirements, ERD design.</item>
        <item>16 — Decision Analysis: solution evaluation, option comparison.</item>
        <item>17 — Decision Modelling: business rules, DMN tables.</item>
        <item>18 — Document Analysis: elicitation, existing-state documentation.</item>
        <item>19 — Estimation: planning, effort sizing.</item>
        <item>20 — Financial Analysis: business case, ROI calculation.</item>
        <item>21 — Focus Groups: elicitation, user research.</item>
        <item>22 — Functional Decomposition: requirements architecture, scope breakdown.</item>
        <item>23 — Glossary: communication, shared vocabulary.</item>
        <item>24 — Interface Analysis: requirements analysis, system integration.</item>
        <item>25 — Interviews: elicitation, stakeholder deep-dive.</item>
        <item>26 — Item Tracking: requirements management, issue log.</item>
        <item>27 — Lessons Learned: retrospective, process improvement.</item>
        <item>28 — Metrics and KPIs: performance measurement, success criteria.</item>
        <item>29 — Mind Mapping: elicitation, concept organization.</item>
        <item>30 — Non-Functional Requirements Analysis: requirements analysis, quality attributes.</item>
        <item>31 — Observation: elicitation, process discovery.</item>
        <item>32 — Organizational Modelling: current state, org chart analysis.</item>
        <item>33 — Prioritization: requirements management, backlog ordering.</item>
        <item>34 — Process Analysis: current state, bottleneck identification.</item>
        <item>35 — Process Modelling: requirements modeling, BPMN design.</item>
        <item>36 — Prototyping: elicitation, validation.</item>
        <item>37 — Reviews: verification, quality assurance.</item>
        <item>38 — Risk Analysis and Management: strategy, evaluation, contingency planning.</item>
        <item>39 — Roles and Permissions Matrix: requirements analysis, access control.</item>
        <item>40 — Root Cause Analysis: problem analysis, defect investigation.</item>
        <item>41 — Scope Modelling: strategy analysis, boundary definition.</item>
        <item>42 — Sequence Diagrams: requirements modeling, interaction design.</item>
        <item>43 — Stakeholder List, Map, or Personas: stakeholder analysis, engagement planning.</item>
        <item>44 — State Modelling: requirements modeling, lifecycle analysis.</item>
        <item>45 — Survey or Questionnaire: elicitation, broad stakeholder input.</item>
        <item>46 — SWOT Analysis: current state, strategic assessment.</item>
        <item>47 — Use Cases and Scenarios: requirements modeling, functional specification.</item>
        <item>48 — User Stories: agile requirements, sprint planning.</item>
        <item>49 — Vendor Assessment: solution evaluation, procurement.</item>
        <item>50 — Workshops: elicitation, consensus building.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="common-failure-modes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Weighted-score laundering — weights drift to make the math agree with the pre-decided recommendation.</description>
        <reason>Without weights locked before options are scored (in a separate weight-setting workshop documented), the score is decorative.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Five-point-scale clustering — every option scores 3 or 4 on every criterion.</description>
        <reason>Force anchored definitions or switch to {-1, 0, +1} pairwise vs. baseline.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Missing baseline / do-nothing column — recommendation reads as advocacy without status-quo option.</description>
        <reason>README explicitly says "include do nothing baseline" — agents skip it when rushed.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>No sensitivity analysis — reasonable ±10% weight wobble flips the winner.</description>
        <reason>Always recompute the ranking with weights at ±10% and ±25% before publishing.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Criterion overlap — "Cost", "Time to value", and "Risk" all partly encode the same capital exposure.</description>
        <reason>Run a correlation check or merge criteria.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Ordinal × cardinal confusion — weights are percentages but scores are ordinal.</description>
        <reason>The output is rank-ordering at best; call it a ranking aid, not a value.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Limitation register without root-cause — defects are listed; root causes are guessed; remediation lands on symptoms.</description>
        <reason>README mandates the root-cause column — agents fill it with restated symptoms unless explicitly forced to use 5-whys / fishbone sub-routine.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Severity inflation — without a severity rubric, every limitation is "High" within a week.</description>
        <reason>Prioritization breaks when all items are marked high.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>50-technique table as menu, not method — agents pick a technique by name match without checking applicability.</description>
        <reason>The table is a router; once selected, read the BABOK section for context.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Static weights across stakeholders — finance, ops, and engineering rationally weight criteria differently.</description>
        <reason>A multi-stakeholder weight matrix surfaces tensions that a single vector hides.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/scoring-matrix.md" purpose="Solution options analysis with evaluation criteria, scoring matrix, and recommendation."/>
      <template path="templates/limitation-register.md" purpose="Limitation assessment with root cause, impact, and remediation columns."/>
      <template path="templates/sensitivity.py" purpose="Python script for ±10%/±25% weight perturbation and brittleness detection."/>
    </templates>

